What is the remainder of $5^{2010}$ when it is divided by 7?
inference:
We want to find the remainder of $5^{2010}$ when divided by 7. We look for a pattern in the powers of 5 modulo 7:
$5^1 \equiv 5 \pmod{7}$
$5^2 \equiv 25 \equiv 4 \pmod{7}$
$5^3 \equiv 5^2 \cdot 5 \equiv 4 \cdot 5 \equiv 20 \equiv 6 \pmod{7}$
$5^4 \equiv 5^3 \cdot 5 \equiv 6 \cdot 5 \equiv 30 \equiv 2 \pmod{7}$
$5^5 \equiv 5^4 \cdot 5 \equiv 2 \cdot 5 \equiv 10 \equiv 3 \pmod{7}$
$5^6 \equiv 5^5 \cdot 5 \equiv 3 \cdot 5 \equiv 15 \equiv 1 \pmod{7}$
The remainders repeat every 6 powers.
We want to find the remainder when 2010 is divided by 6.
$2010 = 6 \cdot 335 + 0$
Since the remainder is 0, $5^{2010} \equiv 5^6 \cdot 335 \equiv 1^{335} \equiv 1 \pmod{7}$
Final Answer: $\boxed{1}$
ground_truth:
We start by writing out some powers of five modulo 7. \begin{align*}
5^1 &\equiv 5 \pmod{7} \\
5^2 &\equiv 4 \pmod{7} \\
5^3 &\equiv 6 \pmod{7} \\
5^4 &\equiv 2 \pmod{7} \\
5^5 &\equiv 3 \pmod{7} \\
5^6 &\equiv 1 \pmod{7}
\end{align*}Therefore, we have that $5^6 \equiv 1$ modulo 7. Thus, $5^{2010} \equiv (5^6)^{335} \equiv 1^{335} \equiv \boxed{1}$ modulo 7.
